es":"Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ieuan ap Gruffudd was born about 1340, in Wales, his father, Gruffudd ap Howel, was 31 and his mother, Daughter verch Rhys Lloyd, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Gwellian verch Ieuan ab Gruffudd Goch ap Philip ap Iowerth ap Maredudd ap Madog Danwr."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1375":"1375","ABT    1370":"umbes 1370","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","about 1375":"umbes 1375","1390":"1390","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Wales":"Wales","of Hendreforfudd,Corwen,Mer